# Architecture & Separation of Concerns

## Layer Diagram

```
PDF/CSV/Image
     ↓
[ Parser ]          src/lib/parseStatement.ts, src/lib/csv-import.ts
     ↓ ParsedStatementData (JSON)
[ API Route ]       src/app/api/parse/route.ts  ← only layer that writes to DB
     ↓
[ Firestore ]       statements/{id}.parsedData
     ↓
[ Aggregation ]     src/lib/consolidate.ts, src/lib/extractTransactions.ts
     ↓ ParsedStatementData (JSON)
[ Business Rules ]  src/lib/applyRules.ts, src/lib/balanceMarkers.ts, src/lib/incomeEngine.ts
     ↓
[ UI / API Routes ] src/app/account/**, src/app/api/user/**
```

## Rules

### 1. Parser is read-only
- `parseStatement.ts` and CSV import helpers MUST NOT import from `firebase-admin` or any DB client.
- The parser receives raw bytes and returns `ParsedStatementData` JSON. Nothing else.

### 2. Only API routes write to the database
- DB reads/writes live exclusively in `src/app/api/**` route handlers.
- `src/lib/**` modules are pure functions — they accept and return plain data.

### 3. Standard data contract
- All data passed between layers uses `ParsedStatementData` (and its sub-types) from `src/lib/types.ts`.
- Never invent ad-hoc shapes inside a route and pass them raw to another layer.

### 4. Business rules are separate from aggregation
- `applyRules.ts` applies user category rules to already-parsed data. It MUST NOT re-parse or call the DB.
- `consolidate.ts` aggregates multiple `ParsedStatementData` objects. It MUST NOT apply UI logic.

### 5. Cross-layer changes require permission
- If a fix requires modifying **two or more layers** (e.g. parser + DB route, or aggregation + UI), 
  stop and ask the user for permission before writing any code.

### 6. Income is never modified by expense rules
- `applyRulesAndRecalculate` (business rules layer) only touches `expenses`. 
- `income` data is owned by the parser output and must be preserved as-is through aggregation.
